195: The following runtime flags are provided to adjust the requirements of OCSP responses and override
196: the OCSP policy. These flags default to ``true``.
197: 
198: * ``envoy.reloadable_features.require_ocsp_response_for_must_staple_certs``: Disabling this allows
199:   the operator to omit an OCSP response for must-staple certs in the config.
200: * ``envoy.reloadable_features.check_ocsp_policy``: Disabling this will disable OCSP policy
201:   checking. OCSP responses are stapled when available if the client supports it, even if the
202:   response is expired. Stapling is skipped if no response is present.
203: ","endLine":203,"startLine":194},{"content":"184: :ref:`DownstreamTlsContexts <envoy_v3_api_msg_extensions.transport_sockets.tls.v3.DownstreamTlsContext>`
185: support an ``ocsp_staple_policy`` field to control whether Envoy should stop using a certificate or
186: continue without stapling when its associated OCSP response is missing or expired.
187: Certificates marked as `must-staple <https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc7633>`_ require a
188: valid OCSP response regardless of the OCSP staple policy. In practice, a must-staple certificate causes
189: cEnvoy to behave as if the OCSP staple policy is :ref:`MUST_STAPLE<envoy_v3_api_enum_value_extensions.transport_sockets.tls.v3.DownstreamTlsContext.OcspStaplePolicy.MUST_STAPLE>`.
190: Envoy will not use a must-staple certificate for new connections after its OCSP response expires.
191: 
192: OCSP responses are never stapled to TLS requests that do not indicate support for OCSP stapling
193: via the ``status_request`` extension.
